With the upcoming midterms it seems likely that if anything President Biden's approval rating will decrease and not increase. It has not been higher than 50% since he first took office and it seems extremely unlikely that it would go back up to that point given the general rise and fall of approval ratings around elections for the current President.

In normal political times, a) Presidential approval rates decrease over time and b) changes of 4% or more in the approval rating would occur over months, not over weeks - the changes are very small increments. Extreme depatures from the current rating (lower than 38 or higher than 46%) in the next 3 weeks are highly unlikely. Overall, the question is therefore whether I believe that he can maintain his current approval rating or will go below it, and I think the odds are 2:3 that he will maintain his current approval rating, which at the time of closure of this task is 42.7.

Currently, Joe Biden's approval stands at 42.5% and since taking office, his approval rating has fluctuated between approximately 38% and 55%. Based on historic data on presidential approval, this height of approval ratings is unlikely to occur again. Biden's approval has mostly hovered between 40% and 45%, making it likely that barring a major national event, his approval rating will stay in this range in the weeks to come.

The factors to consider here are: 1) Average approval rating for US presidents during this time of their term, 2) Biden's highest and lowest points since his presidency, 3) any potential events that could chip away or boost his ratings. Given his highest to lowest rating ranges from 55-37.5, I considered these the outer ranges as I cannot think of any drastic event. One could argue that timeline for the student loan forgiveness claims, an event in Russia, or midterm campaigning could have relatively big effect, but I considered their probability and magnitude of impact in my assessment.

While this might change with the upcoming midterm elections, I don't expect a large fluctuation in the next 3 weeks.

The estimates for 21/09 are that Biden stands at 42.4%. Biden's approval rate hasn't been higher than 46% since September 19, 2021, and I I don't see the current approval rate reaching more than 46% before October 14, hence the 0% probability attributed. As for below 38%, that happened around mid-July this year but getting to this approval rate from a similar rate to today's took more than two months (he stood at 42.4% early May 2022). So the probability is very low to reflect this. Since he is currently at more than 42% but still close to the lower band of 42%, I put the probability of 50% that he would remain higher than 42% but lower than 46%.

Usually when presidents come into office on or near a crisis (WWII, 9/11, etc) then their popularity tends to wane down significantly. Biden hasn't been a popular president to begin with and unless US goes to war with China, I don't foresee a catastrophic crisis ahead (especially in the next 3 weeks) that will make me thing much is going to change

Since the election, Biden's approval rating has hovered between 40-43%, with a few instances when it was higher (when he was first elected (45%)) and lower (when all his legislative proposals were imploding (38%). It strains credulity that he would somehow get over the 46% approval rating unless there's an event which involves a "rallying around the flag." Barring some catastrophic event (which could happen), I think it is relatively unlikely we'll see Biden's approval ratings back in the high 30's. I think the most likely scenario is that he hovers around 40ish, with the second most likely being a little higher than 42%.

Of the last 4 presidents, only GWB had an approval rating above 50% at that point of their presidency. None had below 40. Biden's current approval rating is 42.3%. If economic conditions and favorable media coverage continues, his approval rating might improve. Conversely, poor inflation figures might cause his rating to stagnate or decrease.

Biden's approval rating has not been >50% since August 2021, so I think it is similarly unlikely that it increases ~8 percentage points in the next month.

President Biden's approval rating has been steady at around 42 -43% for several weeks. I think it will remain around this level as the mid-term elections approach and the president and his party hit the campaign trail to sell their agenda and highlight their accomplishments (infrastructure bill, Inflation Reduction Act, etc.). I do not think his approval rating will go higher (absent some national tragedy) because the Republicans will also be campaigning on their agenda.

I think his approval rating will be equal or slightly higher than where it is today

It is currently at 39% and barring any major black swan events, his approval rating is unlikely to change in the next several weeks.
